Fig. 3
a and 3b provide SEM images of the samples. The powder samples Eu-MOF and CDs@ Eu-MOF are irregular slender particles with basically the same shape, but the particle size of CDs@ Eu-MOF is slightly smaller than that of Eu-MOF sample, indicating that the doping of carbon dots does not change the basic morphology of the material, but has a certain inhibitory effect on the growth of particles. The reason for the regulation may be that there are abundant carboxyl groups on the surface of carbon quantum dots, forming competitive coordination from carboxyl groups from different sources, which inhibits the growth of crystals. This also indicates that carbon dots are encapsulated in Eu-MOF. CDs were not observed in the SEM images, which may be due to the very small size of CDs entering the Eu-MOF crystal. The lattice plane with good resolution can be clearly observed from the high-resolution TEM images of CDs@Eu-MOF. The plane spacing of 0.32 nm shown in Fig. 1f is consistent with the plane spacing of carbon dots shown in Fig. 4
, which indicates that CDs@Eu-MOF is successfully prepared.[42,43]. Fig. 4 shows the TEM image of CDs. Since the particle size of CDs is below 10 nm and the amount of CDs used in the composite process is small, it is not easy to see CDs by SEM[44]. C, O, N, and Eu are distributed equally throughout the structure, according to EDS elemental analyses of Eu-MOF (Fig. 5
) and CDs@Eu-MOF (Fig. 6
).The elemental composition of Eu-MOF and CDs@Eu-MOF is shown in Fig.S2. The results show that the atomic percentage of Eu3+ in the sample after adding CDs decreases, but the mass ratio of C element increases to a certain extent, which demonstrates the presence of CDs in the prepared sample, which also indicates that the preparation of CDs@Eu-MOF is successful[45].Comparing Fig. 3c with Fig. 3d, it can be seen that CDs@Eu-MOFs particles have grown in situ on PVDF films in a date pit shape, indicating that the CDs@Eu-MOF Film was created successfully.

The luminescence spectra of CDs@Eu-MOF(Fig. 12
                           ) and CDs@Eu-MOF/PVDF Film(Fig. 13
                           ) in different concentrations of NB solution were measured.Fig. 12a shows that as the nitrobenzene concentration rises, the fluorescence intensity falls. The fluorescence intensity of Eu3+ ions at 615 nm is nearly 96.1 % quenched when the concentration of nitrobenzene solution approaches 2000 mg/L.The SternVolmer equation can be used to roughly calculate the quenching performance.The SternVolmer equation, which goes like this:I0 / I = 1 + Ksv[M] where [M] means the concentration of NB,Ksv means the quenching constant (M−1), I0 and I are the luminescence intensity of CDs@Eu-MOF suspension without NB and with NB, respectively. The Stern-Volmer curve (Fig. 12c) showed that the fluorescence intensity displayed an excellent linear relation with the concentration of NB in the range of 0–200 mg/L (R2 = 0.985), and the Ksv was calculated to be 3.46 × 103M−1. The CDs@Eu-MOF powder's fluorescence detection limit (DL) to NB was 0.1598 mg/L according to the DL = 3Sb/K calculation (where Sb means the standard deviation of the fluorescence assay of the blank solution, and K means the slope of the fitting line). The methods of preparing different concentrations of solution are shown in the supporting literature.
